ersing himself in the texts and images that reflected and shaped the mental world of Nazi ideologues, and that the Nazis disseminated to the German public. The party had no official ur-text of ideology, values, and history. But a clear narrative emerges from the myriad works of intellectuals, apparatchiks, journalists, and movie-makers that Chapoutot explores. The story went like this: In the ancient world, the Nordic-German race lived in harmony with the laws of nature. But since Late Antiquity, corrupt foreign norms and values—Jewish values in particular—had alienated Germany from itself and from all that was natural. The time had come, under the Nazis, to return to the fundamental law of blood. Germany must fight, conquer, and procreate, or perish. History did not concern itself with right and wrong, only brute necessity. A remarkable work of scholarship and insight, The Law of Blood recreates the chilling ideas and outlook that would cost millions their lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAntisemitismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aAntisemitism-Germany-History-20th century. 0aGermany-Politics and government-1933-1945. 0aNational socialismxHistoriography. 0aNational socialismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aNational socialism-Historiography. 0aNational socialism-Moral and ethical aspects. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aCarl Schmitt.  aConcentration camp.  aEast European colonization.  aEugenics.  aGerman Reich.  aHeinrich Himmler.  aHitler.  aHolocaust.  aJews.  aLa Loi Du Sang.  aLebensraum.  aNational Socialism.  aNazi ideology.  aPenser et Agir en Nazi.  aShoah.  aSlavs.  aSterilization.  aThird Reich.  aTreaty of Versailles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uht